<s1 id=CalendarCommandSyntax>Calendar Command Syntax
	<idx>Calendar:command-line syntax<sort>calendar, command-line syntax<\idx>
	<idx>command-line syntax<\idx>
	<idx>syntax:command-line<\idx>
	<idx>Standalone Appointment Editor<sort>standalone appointment editor<\idx>
	<idx>Appointment Editor:standalone<sort>appointment editor:standalone<\idx>
	<idx>appointment:looking up<\idx>
	<idx>looking up appointment<\idx>
	<idx>dtcm_lookup<\idx>
	<idx>appointment:inserting<\idx>
	<idx>inserting an appointment<\idx>
	<idx>dtcm_insert<\idx>
	<idx>appointment:deleting<\idx>
	<idx>deleting an appointment<\idx>
	<idx>dtcm_delete<\idx>
	<idx>dtcm_editor<\idx>

<newline>&empty;

<p>Calendar offers the capability to administer calendars and edit
appointments through command-line interface tools, described below;
see <computer>man<\computer> pages for more information about the
commands.

<p>Calendar also provides a command-line method for converting your calendar
(callog) file from one data format to another and for removing (pruning) old
appointments.  See <xref CalendarConvertUtility> for the syntax.

<lablist>
<labheads> \ Use \ To
\ <computer>dtcm<\computer> \		start Calendar from the command line.

\ <computer>dtcm_delete<\computer> \	delete appointments from your calendar.

\ <computer>dtcm_editor<\computer> \	create an appointment and save it in a file.
	You can then drag the appointment file from File Manager, for example, to Calendar.

\ <computer>dtcm_insert<\computer> \	insert an appointment and set the Start, End, and What 
field values.

\ <computer>dtcm_lookup<\computer> \	view your appointments on a particular date.

\ <computer>rpc.cmsd<\computer> \	start the Calendar daemon from the command line.
	You must be logged in as root to do this.

\ <computer>sdtcm_admin<\computer> \	create and administer calendars. 

<\lablist>

<procedure>Command-Line Syntax

<ex>
<term nogloss>dtcm <\term>[<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>]

<term nogloss>dtcm_delete <\term>[<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-d <\term><emph>date<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-v <\term><emph>view<\emph>]

<term nogloss>dtcm_editor <\term><emph>filename<\emph>

<term nogloss>dtcm_insert <\term>[<term nogloss>-a<\term> <emph>file<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-d <\term><emph>date<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-s <\term><emph>start<\emph>] 
            [<term nogloss>-e <\term><emph>end<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-v <\term><emph>view<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-w <\term><emph>what<\emph>]

<term nogloss>dtcm_lookup <\term>[<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-d <\term><emph>date<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-v <\term><emph>view<\emph>]

<term nogloss>rpc.cmsd <\term>[<term nogloss>-s<\term>] [<term nogloss>-d<\term>] [<term nogloss>-g <\term><emph>hhmm<\emph>]

<term nogloss>sdtcm_admin 
  -a <\term> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] (Add a new calendar)       
 <term nogloss> -d <\term> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-f<\term>] (Remove a calendar; <term nogloss>-f<\term>, Don't prompt)
 <term nogloss> -i <\term> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] (Print info about a calendar)
 <term nogloss> -l <\term> [<term nogloss>-h <\term><emph>hostname<\emph>] (List calendars)
 <term nogloss> -p <\term> <emph>symbolic-mode-list<\emph> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-n <\term><emph>name<\emph>] (Modify calendar's access list)
 <term nogloss> -x <\term> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] (List calendar's access and rights)
 <term nogloss> -z <\term> [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>calendar<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-n <\term><emph>name<\emph>] (Remove name from access list)
<\ex>

<p>where the optional command-line arguments are:

<lablist nowrap>
<labheads>	\ Argument \ Description
\ <emph>file<\emph> \	A file containing calendar appointments to insert.
			The file must be in Calendar appointment format
			and can be created with dtcm_editor.

\ <emph>calendar<\emph> \	The name of the target calendar;
	use <emph>calendar@host <\emph> format unless FNS is used at your site.
	The default is the user's own calendar.

\ <emph>date<\emph> \	The date for which to view, insert, or
		delete an appointment.

\ <emph>view<\emph> \	The view to display (day, week, month, year).

\ <emph>start<\emph> \	The start time of an inserted appointment.

\ <emph>end<\emph> \		The end time of an inserted appointment.

\ <emph>what<\emph> \	A description of the appointment.

\ <emph>filename<\emph> \	The name of a file to contain
		the formatted appointment information.

\ <emph>s<\emph> \		Standalone mode for 
		<computer>rpc.cmsd<\computer>.  Usually
		started by the <computer>inetd<\computer> daemon; you 
		must be logged in as root
		and start <computer>rpc.cmsd<\computer> with the 
		<computer>-s<\computer> option.

\ <emph>d<\emph> \		Debugging mode for 
		<computer>rpc.cmsd<\computer>.  Usually used in
		concert with <computer>-s<\computer>, above; prints 
		out diagnostic information to the console.

\ <emph>g hhmm<\emph> \		The time for rpc.cmsd's garbage collection 
		to take place
		using the 24-hour clock.  hh is the hour number (0-23)
		and mm is the minute number (00-59).  The default is 0400.
		If you typically turn off your system at night, you should
		have the garbage collection occur during a period when your
		system is up and running.
	
<\lablist>

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref CalendarFNS> 
<item> <xref CalendarConvertUtility>
<\list>


<s1 id=CalendarConvertUtility>Calendar Pruning and Data Format Conversion
	<idx><computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer><sort>sdtcm_convert<\idx>
	<idx>converting calendar data formats<\idx>
	<idx>data formats, converting<\idx>
	<idx>formats, converting calendar data<\idx>
	<idx>pruning old appointments from your calendar<\idx>
	<idx>removing old appointments from your calendar<\idx>
	<idx>old appointments, removing from your calendar<\idx>

<p>Calendar also provides a utility, <computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer>, 
to prune old appointments from your calendar and convert OpenWindows
format calendar files (version 3) to the new standard calendar data 
format used in CDE (version 4) and vice versa.

<newline>&empty;

<ex>
<term nogloss>sdtcm_convert <\term>[<term nogloss>-v <\term><emph>output-version<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-s <\term><emph>mm/dd/yy<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-c <\term><emph>locale-info<\emph>] [<term nogloss>-d <\term><emph>backup-directory<\emph>] <emph>calendar<\emph>
<\ex>

<newline>&empty;

<p>Where the optional command-line arguments are:

<lablist nowrap>
<labheads>      \ Argument \ Description
\ <emph>output-version<\emph> \	Version 3 or 4.

\ <emph>mm/dd/yy<\emph> \	The date before which you want 
				to delete appointments.

\ <emph>locale-info<\emph> \	The locale name (such as <computer>C<\computer> or 
				<computer>de<\computer>), used only 
				for converting version 3 data to version 4 data.

\ <emph>backup-directory<\emph> \	The directory in which to place the
				original calendar file, called calorig.<emph>calendar<\emph>,
				where <emph>calendar<\emph> is the name of the calendar.

<\lablist>

<newline>&empty;

<p>And the operand is:

<lablist nowrap>
<labheads>      \ Operand \ Description
\ <emph>calendar<\emph> \	The name of the calendar to be converted.  
		The format is <emph>calendar-name@hostname<\emph>.
<\lablist>

<p>If no option is specified, <computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer> will check the 
calendar file for data integrity.

<newline>&empty;

<note>
<computer>sdtcm_convert<\computer> must be run by the super-user (root) or the 
owner of the calendar.
<\note>

<newline>&empty;

<procedure>See Also 
<list bullet tight> 
<item> <xref ToConvertCalendarTA>
<item> <xref ToPruneCalendarTA>
<item> <xref CalendarCommandSyntax>
<\list> 
 
<s1 id=CalendarFNS>Calendar and Federated Naming Service (FNS)
	<idx>FNS<sort>fns<\idx>
	<idx>Federated Naming Service<sort>federated naming service<\idx>
	<idx>naming calendars <\idx> 
	<idx>calendar, naming <\idx> 
	<idx>location-independent naming <\idx> 

<p>If your site uses Federated Naming Service (FNS), calendar naming
can be location independent: you can name a calendar without including
its host machine. For example, to name the calendar of user "jsmith"
without FNS, you need to enter
"jsmith@<emph>hostname<\emph>"; with FNS you can enter
"jsmith" alone.

The default behavior of Calendar is unchanged; you can name calendars
using the form <emph>username@hostname<\emph>. If you want to use the
new way of naming calendars, you need to have the resource
<computer>useFNS<\computer> turned on. You can turn this resource on
either manually by editing your <computer>.desksetdefaults<\computer>
file or by clicking the Calendar Names: Use Federated Naming checkbox
on the Display Settings dialog box; display this dialog box by
choosing Options in the File menu and Display Settings from the
options menu.

<procedure> Calendar Naming

When the <computer>useFNS<\computer> feature is turned on, you can use
both the old and new ways of naming calendars. When you choose Show
Other Calendar from the Browse menu, you can enter simply
<computer>rosanna<\computer> to browse user
<computer>rosanna<\computer>'s calendar. Or you could enter
<computer>rosanna@alto<\computer> to name the calendar directly. The
new names can be entered wherever a calendar name is expected (Show
Other Calendar, Initial Calendar View in Display Settings Options,
Browse list editor, Browse short list, etc).

In order for location-independent naming to work, there must be a name
space set up that holds registered information about where the
calendars are.

<procedure> Calendar Registration

When you run Calendar with <computer>useFNS<\computer> turned on,
Calendar will automatically attempt to register your calendar into the
name space.  Once it has been registered, the next time someone
attempts to browse your calendar, he or she can use just your
username. If you subsequently move your calendar, change the User
Calendar Location field in your Display Settings dialog box and the
registered calendar address in the name space will automatically be
updated the next time you restart Calendar. You can also update the
information in the name space outside of Calendar using the FNS
command, <computer>fnbind<\computer>.

In an NIS environment, auto-registration is not supported because NIS
does not support dynamic updates of arbitrary data. In addition,
<computer>fnbind<\computer> only succeeds when run by root on the NIS
master.

<procedure> Service dependencies

In Solaris 2.5, FNS works with NIS+ only. 

<procedure> Build dependencies

For CDE developers that build <computer>dtcm<\computer>, you need to
have the appropriate FNS package installed on the build machine. For a
2.5 or earlier target, you need to have the 2.5
<computer>SUNWfns<\computer> package. These packages can be picked up
from the OSNet gates (<computer>/ws/on297-gate/packages<\computer>,
for example) or from the packages directory of a specific Solaris
release.

<procedure> Runtime dependencies

If <computer>dtcm<\computer>cannot locate the appropriate
<computer>SUNWfns<\computer> package at runtime, it
will simply not use FNS. <computer>dtcm <\computer>can always run on a system without the
<computer>SUNWfns <\computer>package.

<procedure>See Also
<list bullet tight>
<item> <xref ToUseFederatedNamingTA> 
<item> <xref ToGrantAccessToOtherUsersTA>
<item> <xref ToDenyAccessToOtherUsersTA>
<item> <xref CalendarOptionsCategoryDialog>
<item> <xref CalendarOptionsAccessDialog>
<\list>

